Music 
Beyoncé, the Past Is Calling, and It’s Lady Gaga

By WESLEY MORRISFEB. 8, 2016



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









Photo






Coldplay, Beyonce and Bruno Mars during halftime at the Super Bowl on Sunday.

Credit
            Doug Mills/The New York Times        


Boy, pop is weird.About six years ago, Beyoncé sat behind the wheel of a big yellow truck and fed another woman one of those bodega-bought, plastic-wrapped honey buns. “You’ve been a very bad girl,” said Beyoncé, who had picked up her passenger outside of a maximum-security prison. Together, they sped off, stopping at a diner to poison Beyoncé’s dirty dog of a man (Tyrese Gibson). The passenger was now the cook, and she came out from the kitchen to watch him die, along with everybody else who ate her bacon and waffles.With the diners dead, the two women celebrated by dancing in American flag outfits that land somewhere between Wonder Woman and Apache-era Cher. The other woman was Lady Gaga. There was a phone receiver over one of her eyes and some cord coiling across her forehead. The phone was made of hair. And this was the video for a remix of “Telephone.”That’s not the weird part. That, for Lady Gaga, was par for the course — at least, it used to be. Which brings me to what’s actually weird. At the Super Bowl, the woman who once arrived at one award show in a giant egg and at another dressed in carpaccio; who took a song to No. 4 singing “one second I’m a Koons, then suddenly the Koons is me” — that woman stood atop a platform and belted “The Star Spangled Banner.” She did it dressed in patriotic platforms and a glittering red pantsuit that matched her encrusted eyelids.Lady Gaga had effectively been omitted from the Super Bowl buildup. I, at least, had to ask my Bowl mates who was doing the National Anthem. “Gaga,” they said, and, so incongruous was the answer in relation to my grasp of the assignment that I needed clarification: Lady Gaga? This is a woman who could have concocted a halftime shebang of her own. Instead, she was essentially an opening act for someone else’s: Coldplay’s, officially, but from the standpoint of cultural consensus, mostly Beyoncé’s.In 2010, the idea of these two women joining forces was an event. They were atop pop’s Olympus and, musically, met more than once in the culture’s ample middle. Gaga’s raunchiness and subversion of the celebrity apparatus flattered Beyoncé’s karate-chop feminism. For “Telephone,” Gaga invited Beyoncé into the world of the surreal, which she has yet to leave. Together they became grindhouse Thelma and Louise. It’s a nonsense video, directed by Jonas Akerlund, colored like a candy store, and aping David LaChapelle and, to a looser extent, Quentin Tarantino’s notions of revenge, right down to the unprintable name of that yellow truck, which Uma Thurman used for a triumphant getaway in “Kill Bill.”







