As for the secondary market, StubHub says it does not track the origins of tickets listed on its website. Ticketmaster can cancel secondary transactions if they find out a bot made the original purchase, but Mr. Berchtold said, “The challenge is in finding out that it was a bot.”For those hoping to buy Beyoncé tickets when they go on sale to the general public on Tuesday, be ready to compete with millions of other fans. When Adele tickets went on sale in December, Ticketmaster was flooded with nine million people seeking about 400,000 tickets.“And Beyoncé is such a fantastic artist, there are more people who want to see her than there are seats to be sold,” Mr. Berchtold said.But at least there’s one more chance to avoid this outcome:


            i am so sad the beyonce tickets sold out & the only ones left are $1,800         —
        ѕαndу (@saandyrobles)
        Feb. 9, 2016



