An article on Thursday, “Beyoncé Is Seen but Not Heard,” about the absence of an interview to accompany her September cover of Vogue and the fact that she has not given an interview in over a year or tweeted in two, inspired over 400 comments on nytimes.com/styles and on Facebook. Readers defended the singer’s choice to avoid much of the news media, wondered whether her silence benefited her brand and expressed disappointment that she had not taken a stand on certain social justice issues. Below are some highlights, edited for space.
Read all the comments and the full article.









BEYONCÉ REMINDS ME of Rachel, the prettiest girl in my high school. Rachel never spoke up in history class (the only class we had together). She had a seat at the “cool table,” but conversations would unfold basically on top of her as people talked around her and through her.There is something eerie about a person who doesn’t participate, doesn’t feel the need to speak and connect with other people, to make them laugh and relate and think.We saw Beyoncé stand stoically in the elevator as her sister verbally ripped apart Jay Z. To me, Beyoncé isn’t a person as much as a pretty shell who at some point was told to shut up and actually listened. Bey, I want to hear what you have to say. Confidence is not just a P.R. strategy.


Margaret, New York





Photo









Beyoncé at an Oscars event in February.



Credit

Noel West for The New York Times




FROM ALL THE interviews I’ve seen of Beyoncé in the past, she’s not very eloquent as far as her speech goes. I get the impression that it’s easier for her management to create a superstar persona for her if she doesn’t speak and reveal that the empress has no clothes. Think about the celebrities who have lost a lot of their shine due to their social media accounts.


Ingrid-Rose Williams 




IF FOR NOTHING else, it’s fascinating (and discouraging) to see how people try to fill the media vacuum Beyoncé Knowles has left behind in the last year.Apparently everyone knows her, and they are exceedingly certain that she’s vain, or a vacuous mannequin guided by a legion of handlers, or cold-hearted.When she does give an interview, it will be dissected down to the most minute facial expression.


Ian, New York




I MUST ADMIT that I do find Beyoncé’s silence to be attractive and mysterious. But at the same time her unwillingness to speak out on social justice issues is disappointing.Her silence seems to be in the service of maintaining broad commercial appeal. I fully understand that her primary job is to dance and sing and look flawlessly beautiful, which she does like no other. But I think she could do more.I don’t expect her to speak out and speak up like Nina Simone or Lena Horne, but these are troubled times, and I think that those with stars that burn as brightly as Beyoncé’s have a role to play in the discourse.


Christopher Williams, New York




BETTER TO BE mysterious than overexposed like Kim Kardashian. 


Marcia Siegal




I HAVE TO SAY that she doesn’t come across as daffy in the GQ interview quote. (“She occasionally comes off daffy, as when she told GQ in 2013, ‘I’m more powerful than my mind can even digest and understand.’ ­”) Daffy = silly, eccentric. Beyoncé’s net worth is $250 million, according to Forbes. Her social media following, in the multimillions, is tremendous. She has influence. She has power. That power would be difficult for any human being to digest.


Zara, Los Angeles




I’VE HEARD THAT having a child can take up a little bit of your time.


Jason Rubenfire




MAYBE BEYONCÉ FEELS she is just an entertainer and prefers to communicate primarily through her music. It is career suicide to avoid social media entirely so she does it her way through posting photographs to Instagram and making what appears to be motivational tweets. I am tired of celebrities going on and on about their political views, medical “advice,” and T.M.I. about their personal and intimate lives. Good for Beyoncé for maintaining some degree of privacy.


Lynn, D.C.




I DON’T FOLLOW her closely but my last recollection of her interaction with the media involved them trying to destroy her marriage and her relationship with her sister. Maybe she just doesn’t like the media very much anymore.


Xigxag, New York




HER BRAND DOES not require thoughtfulness or eloquence. Her legions of fans idolize her for her perceived power, beauty and artistic expression. Why say things that could potentially alienate half of them? This way, she can form to the ideals of all of her fans at all times, and secure a permanent legacy.


Joe, Seattle








